<subSubSection id="5D93C8ACFFA0FFFCA7FEFD27FB168136" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="15369B27FFA0FFFCA7FEFD27FEB684A4" blockId="8.[144,759,683,1684]" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA7FEFD27FEA780F1" box="[144,262,684,705]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
The species of 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA6A5FD20FD8E80F0" authorityName="F. CUVIER" authorityYear="1825" box="[459,559,683,704]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Arctonyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA6A5FD20FD8E80F0" box="[459,559,683,704]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Arctonyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are medium- to large-bodied badgers that superficially resemble species of the closely related genus 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA54EFD63FDC180CD" authorityName=", Marmi, Lopez-Giraldez &amp; Dominga-Roura" authorityYear="2004" box="[544,608,744,765]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Meles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA54EFD63FDC180CD" box="[544,608,744,765]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Meles</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="7118E6D6FFA0FFFCA500FD63FD5380CD" author="Allen GM" box="[622,754,744,766]" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" pagination="1 - 12" refId="ref21295" refString="Allen GM. 1929. Mustelids from the Asiatic Expeditions. American Museum Novitates 358: 1 - 12." type="journal article" year="1929">Allen, 1929</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="7118E6D6FFA0FFFCA7FEFC8CFF68812C" author="Allen GM" box="[144,201,775,796]" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" refId="ref21315" refString="Allen GM. 1938. The mammals of China and Mongolia. Part I. New York: American Museum of Natural History." type="book" year="1938">1938</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="7118E6D6FFA0FFFCA7B9FC8CFECE812D" author="Pocock RI" box="[215,367,775,797]" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" refId="ref24920" refString="Pocock RI. 1941. The fauna of British India, including Ceylon and. Burma. Mammalia. Vol. II: Carnivora [suborders Aeluroida (part) and Arctoida]. London: Taylor and Francis." type="book" year="1941">Pocock, 1941</bibRefCitation>
). Externally, 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA565FC8CFDCE812C" authorityName="F. CUVIER" authorityYear="1825" box="[523,623,775,796]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Arctonyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA565FC8CFDCE812C" box="[523,623,775,796]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Arctonyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA620FCAEFE2F810A" authorityName=", Marmi, Lopez-Giraldez &amp; Dominga-Roura" authorityYear="2004" box="[334,398,805,826]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Meles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA620FCAEFE2F810A" box="[334,398,805,826]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Meles</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its naked, distinctively hoglike snout; its pale (rather than black) throat; its pale (rather than dark) front claws; and by the morphology of the subcaudal anal sac, which is situated dorsad to the anus (as opposed to 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA6CEFC2BFE418185" authorityName=", Marmi, Lopez-Giraldez &amp; Dominga-Roura" authorityYear="2004" box="[416,480,928,949]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Meles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA6CEFC2BFE418185" box="[416,480,928,949]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Meles</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in which the subcaudal anal sac incorporates the anus; 
<bibRefCitation id="7118E6D6FFA0FFFCA57AFC35FD4A81E4" author="Pocock RI" box="[532,747,958,980]" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" refId="ref24920" refString="Pocock RI. 1941. The fauna of British India, including Ceylon and. Burma. Mammalia. Vol. II: Carnivora [suborders Aeluroida (part) and Arctoida]. London: Taylor and Francis." type="book" year="1941">Pocock, 1941: 420</bibRefCitation>
). The skulls of 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA658FC56FE3B81C2" authorityName="F. CUVIER" authorityYear="1825" box="[310,410,989,1010]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Arctonyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA658FC56FE3B81C2" box="[310,410,989,1010]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Arctonyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA6B2FC56FDBD81C2" authorityName=", Marmi, Lopez-Giraldez &amp; Dominga-Roura" authorityYear="2004" box="[476,540,989,1010]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Meles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA6B2FC56FDBD81C2" box="[476,540,989,1010]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Meles</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are very different (
<figureCitation id="8DB287A2FFA0FFFCA7F6FC77FF7B8622" box="[152,218,1020,1042]" captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="9.[164,243,1691,1710]" captionTargetBox="[387,1221,195,1661]" captionTargetId="figure-0@9.[387,1221,195,1661]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figure 8. Representative skulls of Arctonyx (left, A. hoevenii, USNM 269073, adult female, from Atjeh, Sumatra) and Meles (right, M. meles, AMNH 88698, adult male, from Gouladah, Iran), of similar absolute size. Scale bar = 20 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5446688" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5446688/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
). Relative to 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA6F9FC77FE768621" authorityName=", Marmi, Lopez-Giraldez &amp; Dominga-Roura" authorityYear="2004" box="[407,471,1020,1041]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Meles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA6F9FC77FE768621" box="[407,471,1020,1041]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Meles</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA69FFC77FDF48621" authorityName="F. CUVIER" authorityYear="1825" box="[497,597,1020,1041]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Arctonyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA69FFC77FDF48621" box="[497,597,1020,1041]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Arctonyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
skulls have (among many other differences) markedly flattened auditory bullae; a more elongate, dorso-ventrally compressed, and much narrowed rostrum; proportionally smaller and more widely spaced cheekteeth; a more strongly curved upper incisor arcade; a notched (as opposed to simply U- or V-shaped) posterior postdental palate (formed by the pterygoid bones) that extends further behind the dental arcade, essentially reaching the auditory bullae; and a reduced angular process of the mandible, which is raised above the level of the mandibular toothrow. On the basis of the close genetic relationship between 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA533FAE0FD6087B0" authorityName="F. CUVIER" authorityYear="1825" box="[605,705,1387,1408]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Arctonyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA533FAE0FD6087B0" box="[605,705,1387,1408]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Arctonyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA7FEFA02FF77878E" authority=", Marmi, Lopez-Giraldez &amp; Dominga-Roura (2004)" authorityName=", Marmi, Lopez-Giraldez &amp; Dominga-Roura" authorityYear="2004" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Meles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA7FEFA02FF7187AE" box="[144,208,1417,1438]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Meles</emphasis>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="7118E6D6FFA0FFFCA782FA02FF77878E" author="Marmi J &amp; Lopez-Giraldez JF &amp; Dominga-Roura X" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" pagination="481 - 499" refId="ref23941" refString="Marmi J, Lopez-Giraldez JF, Dominga-Roura X. 2004. Phylogeny, evolutionary history, and taxonomy of the Mustelidae based on sequences of the cytochrome b gene and a complex flanking region. Zoologica Scripta 33: 481 - 499." type="journal article" year="2004">Marmi, López-Giráldez &amp; Dominga-Roura (2004)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
recently suggested that the two could be regarded as congeneric, but the trenchant external and cranial traits that distinguish these two classically recognized genera argue for their continued distinction at the generic level (see also Bininda- Emonds, Gittleman &amp; Purvis, 1999), especially now that both genera are no longer regarded as monotypic (see below).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="15369B27FFA0FFFCA7FEF94BFD1A855F" blockId="8.[144,759,1728,1903]" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA7FEF94BFE8084E5" box="[144,289,1728,1749]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Distribution:</emphasis>
The modern and fossil distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA7FEF954FF5584C4" authorityName="F. CUVIER" authorityYear="1825" box="[144,244,1759,1780]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Arctonyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA7FEF954FF5584C4" box="[144,244,1759,1780]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Arctonyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is restricted to East and Southeast Asia, incorporating most of 
<collectingCountry id="6D9EDBB7FFA0FFFCA6E0F976FE778523" box="[398,470,1789,1811]" name="China" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">China</collectingCountry>
, the eastern Indian Subcontinent and Indochina, as far south as the Isthmus of Kra; an outlying population occurs on the Sunda Shelf in the mountains of Sumatra (see below).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="15369B27FFA0FFFCA448FF4DFAB2805A" blockId="8.[806,1421,198,618]" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA448FF4DFC6982EB" box="[806,968,198,219]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Relationships:</emphasis>
Amongst extant mustelids, 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA279FF4DFAF682EB" authorityName=", Marmi, Lopez-Giraldez &amp; Dominga-Roura" authorityYear="2004" box="[1303,1367,198,219]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Meles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA279FF4DFAF682EB" box="[1303,1367,198,219]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Meles</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA448FF6EFC2B82CA" authorityName="F. CUVIER" authorityYear="1825" box="[806,906,229,250]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Arctonyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA448FF6EFC2B82CA" box="[806,906,229,250]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Arctonyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are sister taxa, now generally regarded as the only two component genera of the mustelid subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA416FEA9FC758308" authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1838" box="[888,980,290,312]" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Melinae">Melinae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="7118E6D6FFA0FFFCA48BFEA9FB1C8307" author="Marmi J &amp; Lopez-Giraldez JF &amp; Dominga-Roura X" box="[997,1213,290,312]" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" pagination="481 - 499" refId="ref23941" refString="Marmi J, Lopez-Giraldez JF, Dominga-Roura X. 2004. Phylogeny, evolutionary history, and taxonomy of the Mustelidae based on sequences of the cytochrome b gene and a complex flanking region. Zoologica Scripta 33: 481 - 499." type="journal article" year="2004">
Marmi 
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA353FEA9FBD58307" box="[1085,1140,290,311]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">et al.</emphasis>
, 2004
</bibRefCitation>
, 2006; 
<bibRefCitation id="7118E6D6FFA0FFFCA27CFEA9FCFE8365" author="Sato JJ &amp; Hosoda T &amp; Wolsan M &amp; Suzuki H" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" pagination="111 - 118" refId="ref25533" refString="Sato JJ, Hosoda T, Wolsan M, Suzuki H. 2004. Molecular phylogeny of artoids (Mammalia: Carnivora) with emphasis on phylogenetic and taxonomic positions of ferret-badgers and skunks. Zoological Science (Tokyo) 21: 111 - 118." type="journal article" year="2004">
Sato 
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA221FEA9FA278307" box="[1359,1414,290,311]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">et al.</emphasis>
, 2004
</bibRefCitation>
; see below). Incorporating fossil taxa, 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA261FECBFAD28365" authorityName="F. CUVIER" authorityYear="1825" box="[1295,1395,320,341]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Arctonyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA261FECBFAD28365" box="[1295,1395,320,341]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Arctonyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is considered to be the sister lineage to the extinct (Pliocene) Holarctic genus 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA309FEF6FB4383A2" authorityName="Stach" authorityYear="1951" box="[1127,1250,381,402]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Arctomeles" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA309FEF6FB4383A2" box="[1127,1250,381,402]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Arctomeles</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="7118E6D6FFA0FFFCA398FEF5FA2983A3" author="Petter G" box="[1270,1416,382,403]" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" pagination="567 - 597" refId="ref24873" refString="Petter G. 1971. Origine, phylogenie et systematique des blaireaux. Mammalia 35: 567 - 597." type="journal article" year="1971">Petter, 1971</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="7118E6D6FFA0FFFCA448FE17FBCE8382" author="Tedford RH &amp; Harington CR" box="[806,1135,412,434]" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" pagination="388 - 390" refId="ref25962" refString="Tedford RH, Harington CR. 2003. An Arctic mammal fauna from the Early Pliocene of North America. Nature 425: 388 - 390." type="journal article" year="2003">Tedford &amp; Harington, 2003</bibRefCitation>
). The close relationship between the Holarctic genus 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA315FE30FB5783E0" authorityName="Stach" authorityYear="1951" box="[1147,1270,443,464]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Arctomeles" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA315FE30FB5783E0" box="[1147,1270,443,464]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Arctomeles</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the temperate Old World genus 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA358FE52FBD783DE" authorityName=", Marmi, Lopez-Giraldez &amp; Dominga-Roura" authorityYear="2004" box="[1078,1142,473,494]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Meles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA358FE52FBD783DE" box="[1078,1142,473,494]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Meles</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the temperate to tropical Old World genus 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA33BFE73FB18803D" authorityName="F. CUVIER" authorityYear="1825" box="[1109,1209,504,525]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Arctonyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA33BFE73FB18803D" box="[1109,1209,504,525]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Arctonyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
provides a strong indication that the occurrence of 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA3A3FD9CFA90801C" authorityName="F. CUVIER" authorityYear="1825" box="[1229,1329,535,556]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Arctonyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA3A3FD9CFA90801C" box="[1229,1329,535,556]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Arctonyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the tropics is a comparatively novel development in the historical biogeography of meline badgers.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="15369B27FFA0FFFCA448FD1FFB168136" blockId="8.[806,1421,660,774]" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA448FD1FFC248099" box="[806,901,660,681]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">Content:</emphasis>
We recognize three extant species of 
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA448FD38FC0780F8" box="[806,934,691,712]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA448FD38FC2B80F8" authorityName="F. CUVIER" authorityYear="1825" box="[806,906,691,712]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Arctonyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Arctonyx</taxonomicName>
–
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA4DAFD38FB5680F8" authority="F. Cuvier, 1825" authorityName="F. Cuvier" authorityYear="1825" box="[948,1271,690,712]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Arctonyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="collaris">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA4DAFD38FB8F80F7" box="[948,1070,690,712]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">A. collaris</emphasis>
F. Cuvier, 1825
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA267FD38FC4C80D7" authority="(Hubrecht, 1891)" baseAuthorityName="Hubrecht" baseAuthorityYear="1891" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Arctonyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hoevenii">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA267FD38FA2C80F7" box="[1289,1421,690,712]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">A. hoevenii</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="7118E6D6FFA0FFFCA440FD5AFC4580D7" author="Hubrecht AAW" box="[814,996,721,743]" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" pagination="241 - 242" refId="ref23364" refString="Hubrecht AAW. 1891. A new mammal from Sumatra. Notes Leyden Museum 13: 241 - 242." type="journal article" year="1891">Hubrecht, 1891</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
; and 
<taxonomicName id="D289E0A4FFA0FFFCA35EFD5AFAD480D7" authority="(Blyth, 1853)" baseAuthorityName="Blyth" baseAuthorityYear="1853" box="[1072,1397,721,743]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Meles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="albogularis">
<emphasis id="27FD4735FFA0FFFCA35EFD5AFB7580D6" box="[1072,1236,721,742]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="361">A. albogularis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="7118E6D6FFA0FFFCA388FD5AFACC80D7" author="Blyth E" box="[1254,1389,721,743]" pageId="8" pageNumber="361" pagination="589 - 594" refId="ref21640" refString="Blyth E. 1853. Report of zoological curator for September meeting. Journal of the Asiatic Society of Bengal 22: 589 - 594." type="journal article" year="1853">Blyth, 1853</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
– as diagnosed and discussed below.
</paragraph>
